  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "Explain the difference between BFS and DFS graph traversal. When is each preferred?",
  "response_text": "Breadth-First Search (BFS) and Depth-First Search (DFS) are two fundamental algorithms used for traversing or searching tree or graph data structures. The primary difference between them lies in their approach to exploring nodes.\n\n**Breadth-First Search (BFS):**\n- **Approach:** BFS explores all the vertices of a graph level by level. It starts from the root node (or an arbitrary starting node) and visits all the neighboring nodes at the present depth prior to moving on to nodes at the next depth level.\n- **Data Structure Used:** A queue is used to keep track of the next vertex to visit.\n- **Use Case:** BFS is typically used when we want to find the shortest path in an unweighted graph or when we need to explore all nodes at a given distance from the source node.\n\n**Depth-First Search (DFS):**\n- **Approach:** DFS explores as far down a branch as it can before backtracking. It starts from the root node and goes as deep as possible along each branch before backtracking.\n- **Data Structure Used:** A stack (or recursion) is used to keep track of the next vertex to visit.\n- **Use Case:** DFS is often used for tasks such as topological sorting, detecting cycles in a graph, and finding connected components in a graph. It is also used in scenarios where the goal is to explore all possible paths, such as in maze solving or in finding all possible solutions to a problem.\n\n**When to Use Each:**\n- **BFS is preferred** when:\n  - You need to find the shortest path in an unweighted graph.\n  - You want to explore all nodes at a given distance from the source node.\n  - You are dealing with a tree structure and need to ensure that all nodes are visited in a level-by-level manner.\n\n- **DFS is preferred** when:\n  - You need to explore all possible paths or solutions.\n  - You are looking for a specific node and want to go as deep as possible to find it.\n  - You are working with a graph that has cycles and need to detect them.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 9\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
